  "prompt": "What is infant mortality rate?",
  "response": "The **infant mortality rate (IMR)** is a key demographic indicator that measures the number of deaths of infants under one year of age per 1,000 live births in a given year. It is an important measure of the overall health and well-being of a population, reflecting the quality of healthcare, socioeconomic conditions, and access to essential services like nutrition and sanitation.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Calculation**:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Infant Mortality Rate} = \\left( \\frac{\\text{Number of Infant Deaths}}{\\text{Number of Live Births}} \\right) \\times 1000\n   \\]\n\n2. **Significance**:\n   - A high IMR often indicates poor healthcare infrastructure, poverty, or inadequate maternal and child health services.\n   - It is used by governments, health organizations, and researchers to assess public health policies and interventions.\n\n3. **Global Trends**:\n   - IMR varies widely across countries, with lower rates in developed nations and higher rates in low-income and developing regions.\n   - Globally, IMR has declined significantly over the past few decades due to improvements in healthcare, sanitation, and education.\n\n4. **Leading Causes**:\n   Common causes of infant mortality include:\n   - **Neonatal causes** (e.g., preterm birth, birth asphyxia, infections).\n   - **Postneonatal causes** (e.g., malnutrition, infectious diseases, accidents).\n\nReducing infant mortality is a major goal of global health initiatives like the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs).",
